# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Line Ending Strategy - Consistent across Windows/Linux/macOS
# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Reference: https://help.github.com/articles/dealing-with-line-endings/
# Problem: Git auto-converts line endings, causing unwanted diffs
# Solution: Explicitly declare line endings per file type

# Default: Unix (LF) for consistency across CI/CD and development environments
* text eol=lf

# Windows batch/PowerShell: Must use CRLF (Windows-native line ending)
*.bat           text eol=crlf
*.cmd           text eol=crlf
*.ps1           text eol=crlf

# Shell scripts (Gradle wrapper, CI/CD): Unix LF required
/gradlew        text eol=lf
shell/**        text eol=lf

# Binary files: Prevent Git from modifying them
*.jar binary
*.class binary
*.zip binary
*.png binary
*.jpg binary

